This macro will be a bit more abstract since macros don't operate at runtime and can't inspect the values of variables, but they can check if a certain pattern (like the presence of an argument) matches.

The following macro definition checks if the `dynamic_tags` identifier is present in the argument list and executes different code branches accordingly:

```rust
macro_rules! check_dynamic_tags {
    // Pattern matches if `dynamic_tags` identifier is present.
    ($($key:ident : $value:expr),*, dynamic_tags: $($dynamic_tags:expr),*) => {
        {
            // Code branch when `dynamic_tags` is present.
            println!("dynamic_tags has been passed in!");
            // Handle the dynamic_tags here as needed.
        }
    };
    // Pattern matches if there are arguments, but `dynamic_tags` identifier is not present.
