// This is a conceptual answer, not a code snippet.
// Java achieves platform independence through the use of bytecode and the Java Virtual Machine (JVM).
// When you compile a Java program, the Java compiler converts the source code into bytecode, which is a platform-independent code.
// The JVM, specific to each platform, interprets this bytecode and executes it, thus allowing the same Java program to run on different platforms.
```

